Big Data¶

  • What is Big Data?

  • Processing

    • Vertical Scaling "Scaling up"
    • Horizontal Scaling "Scaling Out"

Tools for Big Data Processing¶

  • Apache Spark

    • Clusters
    • Actions

  • Spark APIs

    • PySpark (Python)
    • SparkR (R)
    • Sparklyr(R)
  • Resilient Distributed Datasets (RDD)
    • Spark's core data structure
    • Nodes
    • Fault-tolerant
    • Dataframes
  • Databricks
    • Notebook Format
    • Python, R, SQL
    • Spark native
    • Cloud-optimized platform

PySpark vs Pandas¶

  • PySpark (Spark API)
    • Two main libraries
      • Spark SQL (Big Data)
      • MLlib (Machine Learning)
    • Lazy Evaluation
      • Conserve and plan processing power
      • Optimized big data processing
      • Must call action
      • show() count()
  • Pandas
    • No need for actions

  • Pandas

    • df = pd.read_csv ("data.csv")
    • df
    • numpy

  • Pyspark

    • df1 = spark.read.csv("data.csv", header = True, inferSchema = True)
    • df1.show()
    • pyspark.sql.functions

Processing Big Data¶

  • Cloud Computing

    • Virtual Machines (VMs)
    • Storage
    • Databases

  • Cloud Providers

    • Computational power
    • AWS, Azure, Google Cloud

Part 2 Analysis¶

1. Upload the dataset to your Databricks filestore¶

2. Read in the data and call it df¶

In [0]:
%python 
import pyspark.sql.functions as F
# File location and type
file_location = "/FileStore/tables/bank_transactions.csv"
file_type = "csv"

# CSV options
infer_schema = "True"
first_row_is_header = "True"
delimiter = ","

# The applied options are for CSV files. For other file types, these will be ignored.
df = spark.read.format(file_type) \
  .option("inferSchema", infer_schema) \
  .option("header", first_row_is_header) \
  .option("sep", delimiter) \
  .load(file_location)

display(df)

show() is an action, which begins Spark processing. The output in #5 won't actually run until you write a command for Spark to display the results. This is accomplished with the display() command. Output in #6 will run automatically because of the inclusion of the command show(). show accomplishes the same thing as display¶

9. Write a SQL query to count the number of transaction by type and return the result in descending order. Generate a bar plot of the results using Databricks’ plot options. Explain the results.¶

In [0]:
%sql
SELECT COUNT(*) as number, type as transaction_type
FROM df_table
GROUP BY transaction_type
ORDER BY number DESC;
numbertransaction_type
2237500CASH_OUT
2151495PAYMENT
1399284CASH_IN
532909TRANSFER
41432DEBIT

These results show that the most common types of transactions by far are Cash outs and Payments. After that for transaction frequency come Cash Ins, Transfers, and Debits. Debits make up a tiny proportion of the overall number of transactions.¶

10. Create a new column that labels the transaction as suspicious. The new column should be called label and take the value of 1 if:¶

  • The oldbalanceOrg is less than 54000 and the type of transaction is a transfer and the new balance is less than or equal to 105, or
  • The oldbalanceOrg is greater than 56900 and he newbalanceOrig is less than or equal to 12, or
  • The oldbalanceOrg is greater than 56900 and the newbalanceOrig is greater than 12 and the amount is greater than 1160000,
In [0]:
%python
import pyspark.sql.functions as F

df1 = df1.withColumn("label", F.when(
                    (df1["oldbalanceOrg"] < 54000) & (df1["type"] == "TRANSFER") & (df1["newbalanceOrig"] <=105) |
                    (df1["oldbalanceOrg"] > 56900) & (df1["newbalanceOrig"] <= 12) |
                    (df1["oldbalanceOrg"] > 56900) & (df1["newbalanceOrig"] > 12) & (df["amount"] > 1160000),
                    1).otherwise(0))
display(df1)

12. Calculate the percentage of transactions labeled suspicious (“label”) out of all transactions¶

In [0]:
%python
sus = df1.filter(df1["label"] == 1).count()
total = df1.count()
perc = (sus / total) * 100
str(round(perc, 2))
Out[14]: '10.92'

13. Import StringIndexer, OneHotEncoder, and VectorAssembler from pyspark. Explain what each of these PySpark processing tools is used for.¶

In [0]:
%python
## ML Pre-processing
from pyspark.ml.feature import StringIndexer
from pyspark.ml.feature import OneHotEncoder
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler

StringIndexer is used to convert categorical features/variables to numeric vectors. Aso converts binary categorical columns to binary vectors as labels or features. OneHotEncoder maps label indices to a binary representation using a sparse vector. VectorAssembler combines all features columns into a single feature vector that's required by Spark MLlib¶

14. Convert the column “type” to a numeric column of indices called typeIdx¶

In [0]:
%python
df1 = StringIndexer(inputCol = "type", outputCol = "typeldx").fit(df1).transform(df1)

%python
df1.show()

15. Encode “typeIdx” to create a binary representation of it called “type_bins”¶

In [0]:
%python
df1 = OneHotEncoder(inputCol = "typeldx", outputCol = "type_bins").fit(df1).transform(df1)


%python
display(df1)

16. The “type_bins” feature is stored as a SparseVector. What is a SparseVector and why does Spark use it to store data?¶

  • Assemble the columns into a single vector column with the following input columns: "type_bins","amount","oldbalanceOrg", "newbalanceOrig", "oldbalanceDest", "newbalanceDest", "destination_diff". Call the output column features and select features and label.

A sparse vector hides the zeroes in a vector. Spark does this in order to conserve space.A sparse vector specifies the size of the vector, the vector positions that are non-zero, and the values of those non-zero positions.¶

In [0]:
%python
modeling_df = VectorAssembler(inputCols = ["type_bins",
                                           "amount",
                                           "oldbalanceOrg",
                                           "newbalanceOrig",
                                           "oldbalanceDest",
                                           "newbalanceDest",
                                           "destination_diff"],
                             outputCol = "features").transform(df1).select("features", "label")
modeling_df.show()

22. Evaluate the model using the BinaryClassificationEvaluator by using the predictions to get the Area under the ROC and save this number as a variable called dt_auc.¶

In [0]:
%python
from pyspark.ml.evaluation import BinaryClassificationEvaluator

#instantiate evaluator object
evaluator = BinaryClassificationEvaluator(labelCol = "label",
                                         rawPredictionCol = "prediction",
                                         metricName = "areaUnderROC")
dt_auc = evaluator.evaluate(predicts)
print(f"Area under ROC: {dt_auc}")
Area under ROC: 0.973111720340154
